`crates/ctx-summarize/src` is the summarization runner: it turns a set of
repo-relative source paths into leaf `.ctx` files and leaf-up `rollup.ctx`
files by driving an `Agent` completion over prompts loaded from disk, gated
by an `Fs` abstraction and an access/scope check. Depending on this crate
(or invoking its CLI) gets you `dispatch`/`run`/`run_with_prompts` as the
only supported entry points; everything else is an implementation seam
swappable for tests.

The crate is layered strictly cli → runner → {fs, agent, cache, cpath,
error}, enforced in lib.rs's doc comment: runner.rs must never depend on
cli.rs, and prompt strings must never be embedded in code — they're loaded
at runtime from `prompts/summarizer-{leaf,rollup}.md` via `load_prompts`,
which fails closed (`SummError::MissingPrompt`) rather than falling back to
a default. cpath.rs owns the one true mapping from source path to
`.context` artifact paths (`leaf_ctx`, `rollup_of`, `intent_of`,
`context_dir_of`, `ancestor_dirs`); runner.rs's rollup-input assembly and
ordering (`affected_dirs`, deepest-first traversal) both depend on this
mapping and would break silently if it changed shape. fs.rs's
`scope_matcher` (`.ctxignore` + built-in `target/`) is the single
definition of "in scope for summarization," consulted by both the runner's
per-target access check and reused by ctx-scan's walker — do not add a
second ignore-rule source. cache.rs is read-only against ctx-access's task
cache and is the only place `paths_written` is parsed for the `FromCache`
CLI mode.

Each child's role: agent.rs defines the model-agnostic subprocess wire
contract (stdin JSON `{system,user}`, stdout text) and enforces request
spacing; cli.rs is the argv surface with the two target modes
(`FromCache`/`Paths`) and the `--approve` bypass of `scope_check`; cpath.rs
is the path-mapping source of truth (duplicated in ctx-access pending a
future `ctx-core` unification); error.rs is the shared `SummError` enum all
fallible paths return into; fs.rs is the disk/ignore seam; runner.rs is the
orchestration core; main.rs wires real `StdFs`/`SubprocessAgent` and
exit-code discipline (2 = setup, 1 = dispatch, 0 = success).

Invariant spanning the subtree: `intent.md` is read everywhere it's
relevant (rollup assembly) but written nowhere in this crate — no code path
here ever produces or modifies an `intent.md`. Another: `SummError` is the
only error type crossing module boundaries in this subtree; no module
here returns a raw `std::io::Error` or third-party error type to a caller
outside its own file.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.